<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>lobstre.rs rss with inlined content</title><link>http://n-gate.com</link><description>webshit condom</description><lastBuildDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 19:19:02 -0600</lastBuildDate><item><title>Why Rust</title><link>https://christine.website/blog/why-rust-2020-02-15</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/walse4/why_rust"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 16:06:09 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>An app can be a home-cooked meal</title><link>https://www.robinsloan.com/notes/home-cooked-app/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/1xfami/app_can_be_home_cooked_meal"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 10:25:57 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>I implemented 'defer' for c</title><link>https://github.com/moon-chilled/Defer</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/d8g4mk/i_implemented_defer_for_c"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 15:45:39 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>3 tribes of programming</title><link>https://josephg.com/blog/3-tribes/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/1yxtjy/3_tribes_programming"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 17:02:35 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>C++20 is Done</title><link>https://www.reddit.com/r/cpp/comments/f47x4o/202002_prague_iso_c_committee_trip_report_c20_is/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/0inu1m/c_20_is_done"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 15:45:26 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>Other platforms — The Nokia N9</title><link>http://morrick.me/archives/8742</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/f31swg/other_platforms_nokia_n9"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 07:46:13 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>The Horrifically Dystopian World of Software Engineering Interviews</title><link>https://www.jarednelsen.dev/posts/the-horrifically-dystopian-world-of-software-engineering-interviews/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/lhijk2/horrifically_dystopian_world_software"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Fri, 14 Feb 2020 22:05:50 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>Vulnerabilities in OpenBSD's hypervisor</title><link>https://marc.info/?l=openbsd-tech&amp;m=158176939604512&amp;w=2</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/7fhyzv/vulnerabilities_openbsd_s_hypervisor"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 06:50:46 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>What's the best GUI library around?</title><link>https://lobste.rs/s/xx0snw/what_s_best_gui_library_around</link><description>&lt;p&gt;I want to make a GUI.  What’s the least sucky way to accomplish that?  Open to any language, but has to work cross-platform and be free.  JavaFX?  Qt?  Something arcane?&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Fri, 14 Feb 2020 22:14:56 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>NetBSD 9.0 released with new hypervisor, aarch64, updated ZFS</title><link>https://netbsd.org/releases/formal-9/NetBSD-9.0.html</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/7kirja/netbsd_9_0_released_with_new_hypervisor"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 09:46:14 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>Experiences moving from tests to strong typing?</title><link>https://lobste.rs/s/olecii/experiences_moving_from_tests_strong</link><description>&lt;p&gt;I sometimes see the claim that with a sufficiently strong type system applied properly, there’s almost no need for unit tests and less need for automated testing in general: if the code compiles, there’s little opportunity for it to be incorrect.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That’s appealing and I can see how it’s true in some cases. But I struggle to see how it’d really apply to some of the projects I’ve worked on. I’m curious to hear stories from people who’ve become convinced of the truth of that claim. Were there any resources that helped you get there? Anything that finally made it click for you?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here are some examples of styles of tests in my current code base’s test suite that I can’t see how I’d represent as compile-time type checks no matter how sophisticated the type system was. For context, this particular code base uses a CQRS-style, event-sourcing architecture, and it’s part of a payment service.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Can all the historical versions of all the events be deserialized correctly from the event store, getting converted to newer versions (or to completely different event types) as needed?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Does the XML we send to a third-party service validate successfully with their schema?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Is timeout logic executed when expected user actions don’t occur in the required amount of time?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Do our fee calculations produce the values listed in the examples in our product spec?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Do we correctly throttle our outgoing requests when a remote service starts responding slowly?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 13:19:40 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>Situated Software</title><link>https://web.archive.org/web/20040411202042/http://www.shirky.com/writings/situated_software.html</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/dasolo/situated_software"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 17:16:16 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>Evolution of the x86 context switch in Linux</title><link>https://www.maizure.org/projects/evolution_x86_context_switch_linux/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/apsc4b/evolution_x86_context_switch_linux"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 06:55:26 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>Why I still use Medium</title><link>https://medium.com/@enkiv2/why-i-still-use-medium-c052f113c278</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/kmgiyj/why_i_still_use_medium"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 10:51:39 -0600</pubDate></item><item><title>CrossHair: A static analysis tool for Python</title><link>https://github.com/pschanely/CrossHair</link><description>&lt;p&gt;See also the playground: &lt;a href="https://crosshair-web.org/" rel="nofollow"&gt;https://crosshair-web.org/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

